ts", "90": "1. Idea", "91": "2. Related concepts", "92": "3. References", "93": "1. Idea", "94": "In", "95": "physics", "96": "the", "97": "theory", "98": "of", "99": "special relativity", "100": "describes dynamics in", "101": "physical", "102": "spacetime", "103": "in absence of a field of", "104": "gravity", "105": ".", "106": "Specifically, it models", "107": "spacetime", "108": "as a flat time-oriented", "109": "pseudo-Riemannian manifold", "110": ":", "111": "Minkowski space", "112": ";", "113": "trajectories", "114": "of point", "115": "particles", "116": "as timelike", "117": "curves", "118": "in Minkowski space.", "119": "the", "120": "electromagnetic field", "121": "as a closed 2-", "122": "form", "123": "on Minkowski space.", "124": "the", "125": "Lorentz force", "126": "exerted by the electromagnetic field on a charged particle as the contraction of that 2-form with the tangent vector of the trajectory of the particle.", "127": "If instead of restricting to Minkowski space, spacetime is allowed to be an arbitrary", "128": "pseudo-Riemannian manifold", "129": "one speaks of the resulting framework as the theory of", "130": "general relativity", "131": ".", "132": "Mathematically, special relativity is essentially the theory of", "133": "Minkowski space", "134": "as a", "135": "pseudo-Riemannian manifold", "136": ", hence equipped with the constant", "137": "metric", "138": "tensor", "139": "which at each point is the", "140": "bilinear form", "141": "with", "142": "signature", "143": "(", "144": "\u2212", "145": ",", "146": "+", "147": ",", "148": "\u22ef", "149": ",", "150": "+", "151": ")", "152": "(-,+, \\cdots, +)", "153": "or else", "154": "(", "155": "+", "156": ",", "157": "\u2212", "158": ",", "159": "\u22ef", "160": ",", "161": "\u2212", "162": ")", "163": "(+,-,\\cdots, -)", "164": "(depending on convention). The null-vectors in this metric characterize the", "165": "speed of light", "166": ". The linear", "167": "isometries", "168": "of this metric are the", "169": "Lorentz transformations", "170": "and the fact that with the Minkowski metric these also preserve, hence, null rays is the mathematical model for the famous", "171": "phenomenological", "172": "observation that \u201cthe speed of light is the same in all reference systems\u201d.", "173": "2. Related concepts", "174": "speed of light", "175": "Michelson-Morley experiment", "176": "theory (physics)", "177": "electromagnetism", "178": "general relativity", "179": ",", "180": "gravity", "181": "3. References", "182": "Wikipedia,", "183": "Special relativity", "184": "Last revised on January 26, 2019 at 11:38:24. See the", "185": "history", "186": "of this page for a list of all contributions to it.", "187": "Edit", "188": "Discuss", "189": "Previous revision", "190": "Changes from previous revision", "191": "History (6 revisions)", "192": "Cite", "193": "Print", "194": "Source"}